{"key":"processedPost-14579028","value":{"id":14579028,"first":14578617,"last":14585937,"when":1307549922,"utime":"06/08/11 07:18 PM","content":"Flow hoods generate a lot of heat as a function of pressurizing the plenum, and to a lesser degree the heat from the motor itself.&nbsp; You just have to turn the AC off and tough it out.&nbsp; In my area, it rarely gets above 75F outdoors in summer, but even with cool temps, my lab heats up to 90F or more with the flowhood running.&nbsp; AC units tend to collect a lot of mold due to the condensate, so I wouldn't run it near your lab area, ever.<br /><br />Larger flowhoods are even worse about heating up a lab, which is the reason I'm still using my 12 X 24 flowhood, even though I'm running a commercial operation.&nbsp; A larger flowhood doesn't speed up the operation much, but it sure as heck heats up the area more.<br />RR","title":"Re: Air conditioning before using a flow hood."}}